The vessel arrives. The three maneuver through the country of Tunisia, and its capital, Tunis. Another period of time passes, wasted on transport. 

// Perhaps a different storyteller would use this time for conversations to "characterize" the group and their dynamics with one another. But I am not that person. I don't see any need for that. Their ideologies are all exceptionally simple.

// Bernard Zie and Eric Zeety are friends. They've weathered discomfort and the pains of the unreasonable situation each of them have been put in, but it has resulted in some sort of an awkward, tenuous camaraderie. They are "bros", perhaps.

// Bernard Zie and Meryl Leiblich are lying to each other. Bernard Zie is not Meryl's daughter. Meryl Leiblich is not completely clueless about this fact. But they deceive each other and they argue about politics and they provide something the other has never really had in life. Bernard Zie did not have a mother. Meryl Leiblich did not have a daughter that was raised by someone else and so didn't possess the idiosyncrasies that were ultimately her fault or her husband's.

// Eric Zeety is attempting to use Meryl Leiblich's position for the sake of what some participants would disparagingly call 'the plot'. He does not care about her. Meryl was contacted by Eric under the pretense of him being a friend of her daughter who happens to possess information that could lead to the arrest of [PROJECT HEAD], or otherwise disrupt The Antarctica Project. There is nothing interesting about their relationship.

They arrive at a federal building.
